It can reach speeds up to 60-70 miles per hour (97-113 kilometers per hour) in short bursts, reaching its top speed within approximately 3 seconds. Cheetahs are known for their exceptional acceleration capabilities and long, powerful legs designed specifically for hunting prey over long distances.

text.result:
In terms of the fastest land animal found in Europe, it's the pronghorn (Antilocapra americana), not a cheetah. The pronghorn is native to North America but has also established populations in parts of Europe, such as England and Germany. It boasts an impressive top speed of up to 60 miles per hour (97 kilometers per hour) and has several adaptations that aid its exceptional speed, including a unique hump on its back for energy storage and efficient lung capacity to oxygenate muscles during high-speed chases.

While cheetahs are not native to Europe, they can be found in certain countries like Portugal due to human intervention through captive breeding programs. However, if you're asking about the fastest European animal on land without considering exotic introductions, the pronghorn is indeed the winner.
